                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-defend2233" type="age" value="15"></interp>
                  </persName>
             was indicted for <rs id="t18260914-431-off2426" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-off2426" type="offenceCategory" value="violentTheft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-off2426" type="offenceSubcategory" value="highwayRobbery"></interp>
               feloniously assaulting 
                     <persName id="t18260914-431-victim2234" type="victimName">
                        John 
                        Sears
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-victim2234" type="surname" value="Sears"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18260914-431-victim2234" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18260914-431-victim2234" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-431-off2426 t18260914-431-victim2234"></join>
                     </persName>
                  , in a certain field, near the King's-highway, on the <rs id="t18260914-431-cd2427" type="crimeDate">12th of September</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-431-off2426 t18260914-431-cd2427"></join>, at <placeName id="t18260914-431-crimeloc2428">St. Matthew, Bethnal-green</placeName>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-crimeloc2428" type="placeName" value="St. Matthew, Bethnal-green"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-crimeloc2428" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                     <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-431-off2426 t18260914-431-crimeloc2428"></join>, putting him in fear and taking from his person, and against his will, 1 sixpence and 3 penny-pieces, his property
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>JOHN SEARS. I am fourteen years of age; I know the necessity of speaking the truth - I live with my father, who is in the wine and beer trade, in Crooked-lane, in the City. On the 12th of September I was in <placeName id="t18260914-431-crimeloc2429">Hare-street-fields, Bethnal Green</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-431-crimeloc2429" type="placeName" value="Hare-street-fields, Bethnal Green"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-431-crimeloc2429" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-431-off2426 t18260914-431-crimeloc2429"></join>, between three and four o'clock; I had just parted with a school-fellow going to school, but he is not here - I was then going home - the prisoner, who was a stranger, came up - he did not speak to me, nor I to him, but he tripped me up - I had a sixpence and three penny-pieces in my hand, which my school-fellow had just given me, which he owed me at school, where we used to go partners - I do not know that the prisoner saw him give it me, but the prisoner forced it out of my hand - I kept my hand as close as I could, but he got it out and skulked away - he got it out of my hand while I was on the ground - there were some boys in the field, who seemed to have been playing with him - I got up and went to some boys, whom I knew, to get them to assist me, but they were afraid; because the boys, who were with the prisoner, began to throw stones - the prisoner then went and sat down in the field - the others came and took my hoop from me, which my uncle had just given me - McWilliams came up on hearing the noise - I told him what had happened - he took the prisoner, who attempted to run away; I do not know whether he found any thing on his person; I have not got my money since - I was alarmed, which made me go to the other boys for assistance.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-431-person2235">
                  JOHN 
                  McWILLIAMS
               <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2235" type="surname" value="McWILLIAMS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2235" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2235" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer of Bow-street. I heard some persons discoursing outside my door, and I went out - I heard a boy in the field had robbed this lad of 9d. - I took my staff, and went to the field, and he pointed to the prisoner - there were eight or ten boys round the prisoner, who ran off in different ways, and the prisoner in another - I followed and came up with him - I secured him - he asked what it was for - I said "I will tell you that by and by;" he said he would not go; but I made him - I took him to a public-house, where I searched him, but found nothing on him - the house was surrounded with a desperate set, and I was forced to send to Worship-street to get further assistance, before I could get him away.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I was going into my own house, and he took me. Witness. No; he was going in quite a different direction.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. The little boy pointed him out immediately? A. Yes; this was a little past three o'clock on Tuesday, the 12th of September, it was in Hare-street-fields; but to distinguish that field from the others, it is called the High-field.</p>
               <p>The prisoner called -</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-431-person2236">
                  JOHN 
                  MINNOT
               <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2236" type="surname" value="MINNOT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2236" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2236" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a weaver, and live at No. 15, Mapes-street, Bethnal-green. I had been for my work, and was coming home between two and three o'clock - I passed this lad and two more, who were sitting down close by where I live in Mapes-street - when I got to my own door, having nothing to do, I took my young one in my arms, and saw the prosecutor playing with his hoop; I neither saw the prisoner advance towards him, nor did I hear any alarm till the officer came - I then asked the prosecutor if he was sure it was him; and he said, "Yes,<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182609140163"></xptr>it was the boy with the red night cap;" there might be two or three who had red night caps on.</p>
               <p>Q. And so you kept watching him, that he might not do any thing? A. I did not see him do any thing; he was in the field, as he frequently is - a neighbour of mine flies pigeons, and he frequently comes and looks at them; I am quite sure it was between two and three o'clock - it was past three when the officer came.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-431-person2237">
                  JOHN 
                  McWILLIAM
               <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2237" type="surname" value="McWILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2237" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2237" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . There was no other boy there with a red night cap; I wish to ask this witness, if he was not sitting in the public-house, with a newspaper and a pint of beer, when I took the prisoner? Witness. No; I went into the house after he was there; I will swear that I was not in the house till after the prisoner was there.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-431-person2238">
                  HENRY 
                  FITT
               <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2238" type="surname" value="FITT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2238" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-431-person2238" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a swivel-weaver. The prisoner was not near the boy at the time - he was at a good distance; I was playing in the field, and saw the prisoner with a red night-cap on, but no one else; the prosecutor was not long on the ground - he had a hoop which he was rolling about the field - no one took it from him; I did not see him on the ground at all - nor see any body throw stones, nor see the officer - but I saw some man go across the field and take the prisoner; I have known the prisoner before, and played with him often, but not on that day - I was playing with some other little boys - I was not throwing stones.</p>
               <p>Three witnesses gave the prisoner a good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18260914-431-verdict2430" type="verdictDescription">
